Do we want bulk retrieval? ServiceActivity associated to this context object ConsoleLogger used for writing console messages CancellationToken to interrupt the execution Client Request Id for this running instance XAnchorIdentity to use to call the REST api prefix to use to append to signify the type of the xAnchorIdentity True means cmdlet is running in multi threading mode. member.name: M:Microsoft.Exchange.Management.AdminApiProvider.Authentication.MSALTokenProvider.GetAccessTokenAsync(System.String,System.String)
member.summary: Get Access Token asynchronously using MSAL auth Get Access Token for various scenarios 1. It is a certificate based flow and is triggered when user passes CertificateFilePath 2. Context.CredentialUserName and Context.CredentialPassword is present : Then a new token is created based on the values. -No UI based browser redirect 3. If its device auth get the code and print it out and then wait for user to enter it in browser 4. Context.CredentialUserName is present and Context.CredentialPassword is null. It then lands the user automatically to a browser. 5. Context.UserPrincipalName is present : It takes it up as hint and lands him to browser with that UPN populated. 6. Context.UserPrincipalName is null : It takes it up as hint and lands him to browser asking for selecting a account or entering UPN.
member.param: claims param sent by CAE module indicating to AAD that some user's setting have been changed which requires re-auth
the cmdlet id for which token is required

member.name: M:Microsoft.Exchange.Management.AdminApiProvider.Authentication.MSALTokenProvider.GetAccessTokenSilentAsync(System.Boolean,System.String,System.String)
member.summary: Gets an access token silently in MSAL library. Internally it happens in following steps 1. In case of Cert based authentication, there is no user cache and we call AcquireTokeForClient. It uses application cache to get the tokens if it was cached previously. 2. In all other cases it calls for acquireTokenSilently. There is no user interaction here.
member.param: shouldForceRefresh param. This is used by GetAccessTOken to get a new refreshed token
claims param sent by CAE module indicating to AAD that some user's setting have been changed which requires re-auth
The cmdletId corresponding to the cmdlet for which this method is called

member.name: F:Microsoft.Exchange.Management.AdminApiProvider.AuthStrategy.Default
member.summary: In Default strategy we first look up the related token in the cache, in case there is a valid token present then we use it. In case there is no valid token in the cache, then we try to fall back to creating a new auth header silently.

member.name: F:Microsoft.Exchange.Management.AdminApiProvider.AuthStrategy.CreateNewAuthHeaderSilent

member.name: M:Microsoft.Exchange.Management.AdminApiProvider.OAuthProvider.RefreshAuthenticationResult(Microsoft.Online.CSE.RestApiPowerShellModule.Instrumentation.Activity,Microsoft.Exchange.Management.AdminApiProvider.AuthStrategy,System.String,System.String)
member.summary: Check if there is a valid token in the Cache. 1. If there is not token in the cache return false. This signifies that the user should run Connect-ExchangeOnline before running this cmdlet. 2. If there is a token in the cache and the token is not expired then refresh the authenticationResult from the data from the token and return true. 3. If there is a token but the token is expired then try to refresh the token and update the authenticationResult from the data from the token and return true.
member.param: claims param sent by CAE module indicating to AAD that some user's setting have been changed which requires re-auth
member.returns: A bool based on result of Refresh Authentication

member.summary: If there is existing token in the cache, we'll try to refresh the token as per the retry policy. Even after retries, if the token refresh fails, which might happen in case the refresh token is also expired, we will throw and exception which will ask the use to run Connect-ExchangeOnline again.
